column5: **Update 6.24.14**My 128 GB card stopped allowing writes via any of my card-readers Windows PC--either when inside any of several full-size SD card adapters (with write-protect tab either position) plugged directly into microSD slot of reader. MicroSD cards have no write-protect tab so quite surprised worried by this. After failing to find any workable solution by searching online finally put my Chromebook created new folder there then stuck back my Windows PC no longer gave me write-protect error. If anyone has similar problem I'd recommend doing something similar by putting any other PC laptop camera etc have available try writing to there.----------------------------------------------This portion of my review necessarily being written as update to my original review of 64 GB version of card since Amazon disallows multiple reviews for what consider same item. portion concerns 128 GB version of card:I don't need fast card so speeds card not important besides which my test PC not exactly high-end. Therefore didn't count off for speed results got below using USB 2.0 card adapter thought might relevant to some readers. While card did reach Class-10 and/or UHS-I requirements came under 2/3 of claimed "read speeds up to 30 MB/s for fast file transfer." Then again running second PC using different USB 2.0 card reader none of speeds even hit 5 MB/s so seems to highly system-dependent.I only got card week so far works *select* SDXC-compatible devices exFAT-compatible operating systems: some SDXC-compatible devices such as Panasonic HDC-TM40 do not allow cards larger than 64 GB (for whatever reason); was stated manual confirmed card recognized as broken/corrupt/unusable device whereas 64 GB exFAT cards work fine. The 128 GB works fine (with original exFAT formatting) my Toshiba Excite 7.7 Android tablet (predictably) not all my non-SDXC-compatible Galaxy Note 2 (though possibly would if reformatted to FAT32 since 64 GB card FAT32 works fine there).I'll update my review to reflect any problems issues etc notice coming days & weeks.-----------------------------------------------------------------------CrystalDiskMark 3.0.3 (C) 2007-2013 hiyohiyoCrystal Dew World : [url removed as per Amazon rules]-----------------------------------------------------------------------* MB/s = 1000000 byte/s [SATA/300 = 300000000 byte/s]Sequential Read : 18.694 MB/sSequential Write : 11.921 MB/sRandom Read 512KB : 18.502 MB/sRandom Write 512KB : 0.680 MB/sRandom Read 4KB (QD=1) : 3.339 MB/s [ 815.1 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=1) : 1.581 MB/s [ 386.1 IOPS]Random Read 4KB (QD=32) : 3.151 MB/s [ 769.4 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=32) : 1.564 MB/s [ 381.8 IOPS]Test : 1000 MB [G: 0.0% (0.0/119.1 GB)] (x5)Date : 2014/04/24 16:53:49OS : Windows XP Professional SP3 [5.1 Build 2600] (x86)-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------The following my original review of 64 GB version of card published April 24 2013:This high-quality card. used variety of devices through multiple readers different pcs an HD camcorder using micro to full-sized SD adapter never once had problem even works full capacity in *some* microSDHC-only devices once its reformatted to FAT32 (such as my SanDisk Clip+ FLAC player supposedly even PSPs via proper adapter though haven't yet tested my PSP). keep anticipating someone coming out card equal better capacity speeds a comparable price haven't seen one yet. If these cheaper I'd have several by now.Make sure your device can handle micro full-sized SDXC cards one of those rare gems state support only as high as SDHC have been tested to work SDXC cards such as one once they've been manually reformatted to FAT32.

However 1080p protune (bitrate shy of 6 MB/s mode -- much higher then protune turned off) nothing trouble. Camera would sometime work sometime randomly stop recording for no obvious reason. first suspected camera testing different SD cards ended up being SanDisk's card fault. My spare card old cheap 16GB PNY (also class 10) worked fine under same conditions same camera settings.Once obvious problem card found people GoPro's forums had trouble specific card as well (well always find these only after figure out for yourself right?). Anyhow did some speed tests card by doing simple write of 1GB file full of zeros using Unix dd utility to copy 1GB of zeros /dev/zero (where else would find many zeros ;-) onto file card. The result average SanDisk's card would manage about 10.2 MB/s. Just barely above bar for class 10 card. However average over 1GB. During write test speed oscillating many spikes drops. Drops as low as 7MB/s. Uh. thought write speed of class 10 card should never dip below 10 MB/s? For comparison my old cheap class 10 PNY card chugging along constant 13 MB/s under same test. No spikes no drops speed.The card will probably work fine most devices as bitrates when recording 1080p video often low enough and/or camera might have huge buffer. if want to use to record video high bitrates your device doesn't have huge buffer to compensate for speed bumps of card may run into trouble. Be wary of using Hero3 modes have higher bit rates (e.g. 1080p protune enabled).SanDisk's website lists part numbers as SDSDQUI-064G adapter SDSDQUA-064G without adapter. conflicts product description Amazon. While likely Amazon not getting product description right again (a bit too common thing) it's interesting to note.[Update Apr 20 2013]:Some numbers testing card. The test extremely simple. Write out 1GB of zeros onto card using standard Unix dd command to read 128KB blocks of zeroes special device /dev/zero write onto card. 128KB * 8192 = 1GB. dd displays transfer stats once finishes. While dd running run iostat second terminal displaying 1 second interval stats as measure of current speed. was done Mac. dd command line can used as-is to repeat test Linux system however iostat command different Linux would need to modified slightly. choose 128KB block size as seems to what device drivers merges sequential writes into anyhow. Using different block sizes results comparable.$ dd if=/dev/zero of=test bs=131072 count=81928192+0 records in8192+0 records out1073741824 bytes transferred 101.578307 secs (10570582 bytes/sec)So 10 MB/s all good? Right? Wrong! iostat running parallel above dd command recorded this:$ iostat -d -w 1 disk2disk2KB/t tps MB/s123.11 76 9.12116.61 185 21.04122.94 49 5.88128.00 41 5.12128.00 89 11.11128.00 134 16.73128.00 69 8.61128.00 61 7.62128.00 99 12.36[ so until dd finishes writing 1GB of zeros to card ]IMO last column should never dip under 10MB/s for card labeled class-10.For comparison same test run against Samsung Pro 64GB micro-SD card:$ dd if=/dev/zero of=test bs=131072 count=81928192+0 records in8192+0 records out1073741824 bytes transferred 52.869111 secs (20309436 bytes/sec)$ iostat -d -w 1 disk2disk2KB/t tps MB/s125.30 138 16.86117.73 157 18.03123.04 150 18.00128.00 159 19.86128.00 156 19.47126.45 160 19.73128.00 150 18.72128.00 154 19.22128.00 153 19.11[ so until dd finishes writing 1GB of zeros to card ]So Samsung average 2x faster more importantly it's speed much more constant. And critically important never dips under 10MB/s."

column5: My Samsung Galaxy Note 2 came 8 gigs of internal memory. discovered apps can only written to internal 8 gigs of memory so didn't want to fill up internal memory pictures videos music etc. purchased 64 GB San Disk Ultra MicroSDXC Class 10 card. found video youtube to learn how to insert card since could find nothing phone's user guide. It's real easy. Turn Note phone off. Remove Note's back plate. You see plaque saying SD card upper left quadrant of phone. Simply place microsd card face up metallic pins facing down towards right into depressed slot area to left of SD card plaque. Then slowly gently slide microsd card under plaque until clicks. If isn't correctly will tend to move back out under plaque. Do not force. Replace back plate phone. Turn phone on. Go to settings storage. At bottom of page will see SD Card. If microsd card inserted correctly will see additional GBs of storage displayed there. You will also see Reformat SD card Remove SD card. Use these settings to erase data microsd card to remove phone. Do not try to remove microsd card phone without first activating Remove SD Card setting. You can damage card the phone. The card came quickly San Disk reliable brand. It's great to have the Class 10 rating too.

If fill card will take roughly 12 minutes to copy all data off of card assuming device copying to can keep up.The tests done built SD card drive of MacBook Pro using included SD Card Adapter.Based my tests would say if don't need Micro SD then should buy standard SD card your performance might better price should lower. However if think need might need Micro SD down road is suitable solution.

I'm music lover to carry my entire music collection around me everywhere go. That being said takes up LOT of space enough to fill 64gb memory card its own (a lot of files FLAC format.) little hesitant to buy 128gb card when came out recently because 64gb cards first batch pretty much defective resulted recall. Me learning of recall after looking up issues having had to return card bought. SanDisk took 64gb card back without hesitation actually prepared to do without serial number (since couldn't open my phone time because case screwed on.)Note to everyone:Quite few applications don't fully support NTFS newer file system formats such as exFAT. To use your SD card without issues have to format to FAT32 which IS possible even though its over 32GB. Use "Fat32Format" tool made by Ridgecrop Consultants there's GUI (Graphical User Interface) version available for those unfamiliar using command line.------After receiving my new card formatted to fat32 since use lot of applications aren't norm it's easier to use older file system compatible everything made after 1996. The transfer of files swapping of cards seamless my computer's micro-sd card reader recognized without trouble as well as my phone. far everything good there's been no hiccups. Even Google Play has been crashing less when trying to browse my music collection.

column5: Of late Sandisk appears to have lost their way little their flash storage products. It's almost universal truth all of their USB flash drives hopelessly slow; while they're usually reliable transfer rates of 4MB/sec less worthless when filling 32GB drive. Fortunately their "Ultra" line of SD cards still appears to buck trend.Formatted as NTFS used anelago Mobile Nano II reader see write speeds 64-bit Linux machine consistent 15-16MB/sec when copying large (1GB larger) files to card which more than lives up to its class 10 billing. Reads appear to run about 19-20MB/sec.I can't comment reliability as only had card few days everything copied so far for testing has made onto card (and off again) no corruption whatsoever; MD5 checksum of every file transferred matches source. That's more than can said for Supertalent Pico USB drive SD card reader intended to replace which has never been quite right (it's always occasionally randomly corrupted files of larger than 100MB so probability of 1GB greater files surviving near zero).32GB appears to sweet spot moment; smaller cards don't cost much less larger cards beyond SDHC spec into SDXC territory which isn't yet universal terms of device compatibility (not to mention cost far more than double for 64GB).For what paid for around Thanksgiving (not part of any explicit sale definitely lower price than appears usual as far as camelcamelcamel concerned) extremely satisfied.Edit: should also mention included mechanical full-size SD adaptor one of worst ever encountered. There's lot of friction when microSD card inserted it's right bugger to get out of adaptor again. Thankfully have few other such adaptors lying around should ever need one; one's going bin.

These SanDisk memory cards 64 GB microSDXC class 10 UHS-1 cards which rated for transfer speeds up to 30MB/sec.The UHS class 1 designation intended as performance measure indicates card capable of supporting real-time full HD video recording. Of course only works if using device which capable of writing to card those speeds most modern devices offer full HD recording such as camcorders digital SLR cameras cell phones built Full HD recording do support standard. The benefit of using UHS-1 card UHS certified device should not encounter problem of buffering your device stopping recording because could not write fast enough.However because these extra high capacity sdXC cards will need to make sure your device can support microSDXC cards not simply microSD microSDHC ones. The biggest difference microSDXC standard uses exFAT file system rather than FAT32 NTFS systems. While most modern Android devices (and fact most linux/unix devices) can handle without difficulty some devices such as older cameras Android devices some Windows devices may have difficulty format.Having said I've been using these Nikon D80 & D7000 digital SLR cameras as well as Samsung Galaxy S3 Galaxy S Relay 4G phones without any difficulty read & write fine my computers. All all these a great buy happy them."

Although Amazon claim C10 ultra fast Memory Card actually has much slower write speed than other C10 microSD card (it only scores about 60% of normal speed). For example have tested against my old Maxell C10 HC microSD card. The test done by writing same 3035MB random data DRAM to empty microSD card through USB3 card reader. The resulting time average value 3 tests of each device:SanDisk Ultra 32GB C10/UHS1: 5m50.816s means 8.7MB/sMaxell C10 HC: 3m38.787s means 13.9MB/sThe speed completely unacceptable for Class-10 claim (13% lower than 10MB/s lowest boundary of Class-10 device) even over-advertisement of SD card speeds common (claiming 30MB/s for actual 12-15MB/s). almost scam. Some Class-6 card will beat "Class-10" card.

Sandisk replaced under warranty quite hassle to do this.The 16GB card however has been subject to extreme temperatures for well over 4 months: -5F to 100F doesn't include solar loading sitting under sun as well as 100% humidity! The 16GB card dripping water after experienced water intrusion one of my cameras had been soaked water (while operating) for several months.The packaging easy to open by simply cutting across top. However finagling out blister pack took some patience. The Frustration Free packaging essentially cardboard envelope sleeve plastic holder SD card adapter microSD card inside. how shipped!Overall: 4/5 stars. Very affordable decently fast micro SD cards. These perfect for smartphones recording devices used extreme environments. However one of them failed within 2 months. The speeds also inconsistent. posted benchmark photo Amazon showing my speeds all 3 sizes of cards 32GB fastest.UPDATE 28 OCT 2012My 32GB card has failed after over 2 months of use my Samsung Galaxy S3 phone. started dismounting/remounting intermittently by itself over night. woke up morning to find card not readable via the phone wouldn't work my PC. The phone has not been abused not used extreme environment. card replaced under warranty by Sandisk.

[[ UPDATE - 6/19/2014 ]]So my lovely wife bought me Samsung Galaxy Tab 4 for Father's Day been loving ever since. Just as other Samsung products Galaxy Tab 4 has ability to add microSD card to expand memory device. Since it's been over year decided to do some more research to see if SanDisk offered anything new. As of 6/19/2014 their product lineup for microSD cards worst to best (performance-wise) as follows:SanDiskSanDisk UltraSanDisk Ultra PLUSSanDisk ExtremeSanDisk Extreme PLUSSanDisk Extreme PRONow difference between all of these cards simply speed which can read/write data to card. Yes published rating of most all these cards (except SanDisk regular) Class 10/UHS-I that's rating... Actual real world performance does get better each model faster cards come more expensive prices. Since Amazon doesn't carry Ultra PLUS model of microSD card had to do direct comparisons between SanDisk Ultra ($34.27) Extreme ($57.95) Extreme PLUS ($67.95).As mentioned my earlier review purchased SanDisk Ultra for my Galaxy S4. My question did want to pay over $20 more for card faster than one already owned? Or could pay almost double to get SanDisk's 2nd-most fastest microSD card.The Ultra works perfectly fine for my style of usage (storing/capturing pictures & HD video movie playback) my phone. end ended up buying another SanDisk Ultra 64GB card. use my cell phone *more* than do my tablet if card good enough for my phone it's good enough for my tablet. don't own 4K HD camera anything so honestly didn't see need to get one of faster cards time.I am now proud owner of 2 SanDisk Ultra cards have 0 issues my Samsung devices.[[ ORIGINAL REVIEW - 5/1/2013 ]]I haven't had to buy microSD card long time. The last time bought one for my cell phone over 2 years ago. since my cellular contract up knew would have to get newer card addition to my new phone Samsung Galaxy S4. Reason for because knew my small 16GB microSD card wasn't going to cut it.Doing research Galaxy S4 wanted to get best card possible had decent capacity (32 GB greater). led me to find Galaxy S4 supports microSDXC Class 10 UHS-I card which fastest possible given class. Searching for specifically Amazon gave me results of only 3 vendors (as of April) makes these microSDXC Class 10 UHS-1 cards. They Sandisk (the majority) Samsung Lexar. Nobody else makes these sold Amazon.Seeing how SanDisk pretty good name out of 3 (I've used them most) decided upon SanDisk because Lexar overpriced Samsung one overpriced (as well as not eligible for Amazon Prime).But scary when filter by SanDisk get DOZENS of options. All of them have different model numbers different sizes etc. Then there's confusion of what's difference between SDHC & SDXC?SDHC vs SDXC:SDHC stand for "Secure Digital High Capacity" SDXC stands for "Secure Digital eXtended Capacity". Essentially these two cards same exception SDHC only supports capcities up to 32GB formated FAT32 file system. The SDXC cards formatted exFAT file system. If use SDXC card device must support file system otherwise may not recognizable and/or have to reformat card to FAT32.FAT32 vs exFAT:The differences between two file systems means FAT32 has maximum file size of 4GB limited by file system. exFAT otherhand supports file sizes up to 2TB (terabytes). The only need to know it's possible your device doesn't support exFAT. If that's case reformat to FAT32. REMEMBER FORMATTING ERASES ALL DATA!To clarify model numbers hopped over to SanDisk official webpage. What found there offer two "highspeed" options for SanDisk cards. These SanDisk Extreme Pro SanDisk Ultra. SanDisk Extreme Pro line supports read speeds up to 95MB/sec however SDHC only. To make things worse currently only available 16GB & 8GB capacities. Since one of my requirements to have lot of storage ruled these out.The remaining devices listed Amazon's search SanDisk Ultra line. confusion sets because SanDisk separates these cards to two different devices. Cameras & mobile devices. Is there real difference between two marketing stunt? Unfortunately not sure do know price difference between two range couple cents to few dollars. Since wasn't sure opted for one specifically targeted for mobile devices (just case there some kind of compatibility issue). To find exact model number would go to Sandisk's webpage (sandisk.com) compare their existing product lineup. From there get exact model numbers can then search Amazon for these model numbers. That how got mine (SDSDQUA-064G).As for speed tests haven't run any specific testing copying 8 GB worth of data my PC to card took a few minutes.One last note Amazon attaches additional characters to end (for example SDSDQUA-064G-AFFP-A vs SDSDQUA-064G-U46A). The difference between two that "AFFP-A" means "Amazon Frustration Free Packaging". Other than that these exactly same. If you're wondering what got (and want to use in your Galaxy S4) got SDSDQUA-064G-u46A works charm.

No question as fast as it's rated. How fast? class "10 SDHC" means SD format HC=High Capacity Class 10 = 10MB/sec read-write. How fast 10MB per second? Class 4 most common step down (i.e. cheaper) Class 4 i.e. 4MB/sec. Class 10 2.5 times faster. Why pay difference?Digital cameras: some point number of pictures/sec HD video bottle-necked by speed of media being recorded to.Smart phones? have Samsung Note II. Quad-core processor wiz-bang yadda-yadda. Yes DO notice speed differences camera app performance (I use spreadsheet app/browser/NetFlix/Music streaming et al) noticeably FASTER. Where do phone stores stuff to when doesn't use factory installed memory? (iPhomes don't have SD slot wouldn't own phone tablet doesn't -- choice computer realm)Oh yeah SanDisk a leader pioneer SD format (where do the 'SD' came from?). had bought card for my new Samsung Galaxy S3. The card about as good as can expect for price technology you're paying for.SDXC cards come formatted exFAT by default which what would have tried to format as seen if my phone supports filesystem. In addition to being faster format enabling higher transfer rates exFAT also takes up less storage space than say FAT FAT32 filesystem would - which important when considering mobile storage devices.I read several poor reviews about product starting simply stopped working after few months. While can happen regular use as has happened to me past couple 32GB SDHCs would venture to say error use. Flash media sensitive regards to ""hard shutdowns"". that's to say pulling out of your device card reader without first unmounting Within 'Data Storage' menu Android phones there option to 'unmount SD card'. would recommend ALWAYS select before removing any external memory card to avoid corruption of data ultimately card itself. The reason for sudden stoppage of flash memory device's data power connectivity can easily result corruption.Transversely if have memory card plugged into card reader say SD adapter; should first ""Eject"" card. In Windows there small icon located taskbar notification menu for ""Safely Remov[ing] Hardware Eject[ing] Media"". Select card a notification will pop-up card now safe to remove. basically severs same function as the Android 'unmount' optional will also cease any current read/write operations to avoid data device corruption.I cannot speak for how one would do a Mac OS chances if you're using Apple PC don't have Android phone."

They work ok until try recording 1080p video higher frame rates."

purchased card Sandisk packaging so am pretty sure genuine. tested various programs web apparently can detect whether fakes not. one turned out to real Sandisk card. The card came formatted FAT32.I read web about these micro SDs apparently not as fast as full SD card version. borrowed my brothers Sandisk 32gb full SD card to make comparison tests. Here my official/unofficial test results using DiskBench V2.6.2.0 H2testw 1.4 test. will give results as ""overall"" result because after testing these cards over over speed writes reads results get mixed varied to big degree... much larger than expected numerous tests showed me ""general"" trend. The trend full SD cards do write faster than MicroSD card. also remember microSD had to put into adapter to do test my PC while fullSD card put into computer reader directly.These just my averages but:Small file writes:Both SD cards wrote close to 10mb/sec. The microSD less consistent tests sometimes dropped to 8mb/sec.Small file reads:Both SD cards read close to 20 mb/sec their fastest.Large file copies to card:MicroSD wrote 3.5mb/sec while fullSD wrote about 4mb/secLarge file reads copies card:MicroSD 10mb/sec while fullSD read about 14mb/sec.My conclusion:My tests by no means official for card showed much variance dependent file size of reads writes fullSD card faster many cases equal to microSD most cases. The small file writes reads showed similar enough. my only concern large file writes.... 3.5 mb/sec good enough for rapid photography high pixel camera? don't know. have had no problem using these cards H264 movie capture for hours. am surprised 3.5 mb/sec enough.Also never during huge file copies to card did get any noticeable heating of card itself by touch even for hour. noticed has been complaint many people web some stating felt might burn themselves. copied files took more than hour no noticeable temperature change other than perhaps couple of degrees. Of course on PC not installed camera.The card performs well for video work appears to meet many other tests performed by other people. never saw read close to 30 mb/sec... consistent 20 mb/sec highest performance.I would get card again if price right."

The Nexus One listed as supporting maximum of 32GB SDCard.Based reports elsewhere took out my 32GB card put 64GB card powered up phone.The phone reported card defective notification.I pulled down notifications tapped notification issued report. offered to format card.I would note have Clockwork Recovery ROM Manager app installed my rooted (CM7 Android 2.3) N1.After tapping notification phone formatted card. All went well. Since had neglected to move my RootExplorer file manager off SD card prior to putting new card not able to check directly phonethat entire 64GB available. as turned out was.While doing above had been using Winzip to make copy of contents of my 32GB card to my PC (using USB adapter). When completedI powered down phone put new 64GB card PC using Micro SD adapter came card USB adapter for adapter.It showed about 60GB (the usual for 64GB card guess).Interestingly some files (mainly folders) related to clockworkmod had been placed SD card during formatting which shows where formatting codeprobably came from. Take note: if do *not* have ROM Manager / Clockworkmod your phone your mileage may well vary. If have root would suggest obtainingROM Manager Google Play prior to doing above. Anyway deleted those files so wouldn't conflict any of old files aboutto copy.I then unzipped saved contents of my old card onto new card.Then put new card N1 powered up. worked perfectly right away.Root Explorer showed about 60GB of capacity (of which about 30 used by me - needed card!).Tried out Spotify Premium played fine saved files had been old card now transferred to new card. Other thanRoot Explorer haven't tried any other apps yet am expecting good news based experience thus far!I tried full backup using ROM Manager apparently worked without incident.So based above would recommend card for Nexus One! What break to get another 30 GB aging phonethat nonetheless still one of best phones ever.Caveat: Keep mind I unwrapped and have used it for all of two hours.

column5: SanDisk makes lot of claims about card some of them questionable. own two while high-capacity/low-price certainly makes them useful they're not answer to all of my recording needs. First of all do not use GoPro Hero 3 (or later model). Despite SanDisk's claims these cards cannot handle demands of true HD recording. GoPro removed their list of recommended cards because caused cameras to lock up turn off. Even myCanon VIXIA HF10 Flash Memory High Definition Camcorder--technology which over 10 years old--the SanDisk Ultra card does not meet requirements for shooting FXP mode (1920x1080 17Mbps) even though camera says only class 4 required. firmware update to GoPro 'fixed' issue for Hero 3 Hero 3+ cameras did so by throttling recording speed for cards i.e. lowering quality of recording slightly.Those shortcomings aside SanDisk Ultra can shoot XP+ mode (1440 x 1080) Vixia HF10 works all of settings of aContourROAM Waterproof HD 1080P. Is "water-proof temperature proof X-ray proof shock proof"? can't say. The ContourROAM waterproof camera so even non-waterproof cards safe for submersion if they're housing. The Ultra has functioned 10 weather after being dropped so there's validity to claim of being temperature- shock-proof. guess I'll find out whether it's x-ray-proof next time go through airport...

My review little backwards… thought most relevant should go first.WARNING: ONLY BUY THIS CARD ON SALE!The *typical* price since summer 2013 about $24 for 32 GB about $48 for 64 GB. DO NOT pay any more than can actually pay less if have luxury of time / patience.The lowest (non-lightning) price hit about $18.00 for 32GB $35 for 64GB early December. basically buy when price hits $20 less 64 nears $40.00.From December 2013 to January 2014 watched these cards change price almost daily basis. They initially went sale for about $17.95 $34.95 for 32 64 respectively. watched them slowly increase price random dips peaks for month. On January 6th 2014 still show as "Best Deal Amazon" for "7 more days" highest price point since last summer -- higher than have *ever* payed for these cards! don't let "Best Deals" section deceive $27/$50 these NOT "deal" terms of price.Okay here's my actual "review" of these great SDXC cards.****I have tried variety of MicroSDXC cards so far Samsung Ultra UHS1 best -- price can't beat -- for all most important reasons: speed capacity reliability durability.I have not had single failure use these cards my Nook HD+ Nexus 7 2013 (via USB) my Canon 5D Mark II (with converter) MacBook Pro (In card slot). They're durable waterproof can use same card all these devices without reformatting. even had one go through wash still use for pictures.For technically inclined have cards *both* Clockwork Mod bootloader (for Nook HD+) MagicLantern firmware for my Canon EOS 5D II same card. can pull Nook shoot pictures camera look at results Nook by pulling card out of one device placing other. should possible any SDXC/SDHC card turns out Samsung UHS1 only card found works reliably. Some cards won't boot because they're too slow too finicky all my Samsung UHS1s work great (the 64GB will not boot the Nook no 64GB card will).I keep my eyes open for price drops these cards because they've performed so well for me. Samsung also has newer faster card its price-point hovers somewhere north of "prohibitive" so still stick these. And that's good news regardless because as the new card increases its market share these should drop even further price.

column5: have tested dozens of SDHC micro-SDHC cards. One disturbing trend noticed that: speed class rating for micro-SDHC typically inflated. For example 'class-10' rating means card must deliver sequential write speed of least 10MB/s. somehow class-10 microSDHC cards always slower than class-10 SDHC card same manufacturer. Case point: thePNY 32 GB microSDHC Card (P-SDU32G10-EFS2)claims to 'class-10' yet can only write 8.6MB/s maximum while full-sizePNY P-SDHC16G10achieved 13.4MB/s according to CrystalDiskMark v3.01.ThisSanDisk Ultra 32 GB microSDHC Class 10 UHS-1 card (SDSDQUA-032G-U46A) however proves to exception. achieved sequential write speed of over 10MB/s according to two different benchmark programs (11.8MB/s ""CrystalDiskMark"" 10.6MB/s ""H2testw v1.4""). faster than all my other microSDHC cards including two 'class-10' cards fromPNYandPolaroid.A closer look file transfer speed using ""Flash Memory Toolkit"" revealed another nice surprise: For writing small files Sandisk Ultra microSDHC card performed as well as its full-size counterpart theSanDisk Ultra SDHC (SDSDU-032G-AFFP). In contrast all my other class-10 microSDHC cards perform poorly while writing smaller files. See benchmark results uploaded to 'Customer Images' for details.When use memory card digital camera to record HD video needs to store huge video file each session. That means its sequential write speed most critical. When used tablet smart phone however card's random write speed for small files more important. That's why such applications Sandisk microSDHC will perform faster than PNY Polaroid cards even though also rated as 'class-10'.[Bottom Line]As of writing Sandisk Ultra microSDHC card ia actually priced lower than other class-10 cards PNY Polaroid. makes Sandisk best value - especially if need honest class-10 performance across all platforms.[Side Notes]- Do not confuse Sandisk Ultra card withSanDisk Mobile Ultra microSDHC (SDSDQY-032G-U46A). The latter rated for class-6 only.- The size of '32GB' card 29.7GB according to my computer. actually normal because computer people count one Gig as ""2 to power 30"" which 7.3% larger than one billion. 29.7GB translates to 31.9 billion bytes which '32GB' according to marketing people.[Update Feb 4 2013]1. Amazon combined Sandisk Ultra 32GB 64GB cards same product page. Please beware your intended appliance must compatible 'SDXC' order to used 64GB version. My original review refers to 32GB 'SDHC' version.2. There two part numbers for same card. If start Amazon product page select 'Retail Packaging' you'll see part number of SDSDQUA-032G-U46A. if click 'Frustration Free Package' part number changes to SDSDQU-032G-AFFP-A.[Update Oct 5 2013]The Sandisk microSDHC card works great my new Samsung Galaxy S3 without need for reformat (the default format FAT32)[Update Dec 26 2013]My old test results limited by card reader USB 2.0 port used. re-tested Sandisk UHS1 micro card using theTranscend RDF5 Card Readerconnected to USB 3.0 port. Here the results 'CrystalDiskMark 3.01 x64':- Sequential Read speed = 40.0MB/s (was 34.8MB/s when connected to USB 2.0 port)- Sequential Write speed = 13.1MB/s (was 12.6MB/s when connected to USB 2.0 port)"

The primary reason for buying extra capacitySanDisk Ultra 64 GB microSDXC Class 10card to use inSamsung Galaxy Tab 2 (10.1-Inch Model GT-P5113)and am happy to share can get to work flawlessly after some initial glitches. (Read below)Firstly need to aware Samsung Tablet Model GT-P5113 currently runs Android OS 4.1.1 Kernel 3.0.31-523998 Build number JRO03C.P5113UECLK7.(Jelly Bean) My experiences shared level of Android OS your experiences may vary depending what version of OS running. The SanDisk Ultra 64 GB microSDXC card purchased Amazon (Retail Packaging) gets recognized fine however when tablet's Media Device A.K.A 'MTP' application attempts to talk your PC via USB cable Tablet simply reboots! after card presented to PC. - Really strange indeed!This baffled me for couple of hours. Firstly attempted to format card (exFAT) PC formatted fine. After attempted to use tablet to see same behavioral oddity of instantaneous reboot of tablet as 'MTP' application tries to communicate PC. made me investigate issue further determined root cause fact SANDISK now seen to factory format card 'exFAT' also somehow seen to include 'offset' of 16MB beginning of card which shows up as 16MB unallocated region initial sectors card under windows disk management tool.The solution to get rid of 'unallocated' 16MB partition card. You could do PC might require some windows command line experience using 'diskpart' utility what not do not want to confuse people process. For most novice users The process should simple Just insert card tablet use 'native' SD Card format tool under 'settings' Android OS 4.1.1 has will get rid of 16MB partition happily remount Now after simple process 'MTP' application works fine PC to transfer files to SD card without any strange reboot phenomenon.Not sure why SANDISK formats their Class 10 card fashion (They never did with their class 6 cards earlier) there's gotta some technical explanation for why include 16MB partition only SANDISK can give. In end if reformat card tablet (Which defaults to exFAT) card seen to work fine.Bottomline:-----------This awesome 64GB capacity MicroSD card reputed manufacturer for budget minded people gets the job done beautifully. The description quite confusing - says same time class 10 which means should not expect write speed higher than 10mb/sec same time says UHS-1 which means 30mb/sec write speed. The truth as usually somewhere middle close to lower end. have dedicated high speed PCI-E cardreader which use for chip benchmarking. card showed 12mb/sec sequental write speed 34mb/sec sequental read speed. UHS-1 "true" only for read operations meaning if wanted card to speed-up your digital camera speed photography - you've made wrong choice. Just for reference cardTranscend 16 GB Class 10 microSDHC Flash Memory Card TS16GUSDHC10has sequental write speed of 17mb/sec sequental read speed of 24mb/sec. As see cheaper transcend has average 40% faster write speeds!

column5: NOTE: please read last update (scroll to bottom) - leaving review as 1 star as appears to help others who purchased had similar experience.I give SanDisk 5 stars for customer service 1 star for product (for those manufactured past) For those newly manufactured products contain software ROM fix I'd give product 5 stars.To all those who purchased card due to all great reviews.... then used Galaxy S4 (GS4) smartphone for storage solution to problem not one can solve without returning card to SanDisk for replacement under warranty. Believe me tried everything Google searches returned as solutions... formatting as exFAT formatting GS4 then copying data to card while phone etc.... nothing worked... so now please stop pulling out your hair hopefully will get same result which hope to get soon (just RMA'd will send back tomorrow for free replacement under warranty).The problem (As confirmed SanDisk customer support rep when asked specifically asked him):- When used GS4 card will unmount itself inadvertently (may true only for cards manufactured before ROM patch described below implemented manufacturing). can cause data to become corrupt (luckily not my experience) / can frustrating as most of us saving 13 MP camera pictures to card (or MP4 movies stop middle of movie) unmounts when view picture gallery worse right when take picture (this issue experienced).- SanDisk knows about issue. Again SANDISK KNOWS ABOUT THE ISSUE AND WILL REPLACE YOUR CARD. Call them (info below) WILL take care of under warranty. They have good name for reason want to keep (sorry SanDisk about 1 star thought way to get message out to those searching for solution)- The customer rep told me SanDisk tried to work Samsung to resolve issue Samsung refused to acknowledge problem exists card some of their phones (especially their flagship GS4 phones).- The customer rep told me to their knowledge card works fine regular cameras (not Samsung GS4 phones cameras obviously) even worked fine some phones HTC etc. could accommodate 64 GB cards. Hence 5 star ratings others.- The solution SanDisk came up to write patch into ROM of card itself to specifically address issue Samsung GS4 phones (and maybe other Samsung phones GS3). assured new card would get would work flawlessly. will see about 3 weeks.- purchased my card Amazon June 2013 so ones currently being manufactured one should get will have new patch. However as SanDisk manufactures batches (like most of industry) old batches of "unpatched" cards obviously exist warehouses.- asked about software patch could download told it's not possible... hence "hard coded patch" card's ROMSo... how to take care of problem....After speaking SanDisk US customer support (link info below) what learned did.Go to SanDisk site1) [...]2) call consumer products support (this US no.) 1-866-SANDISK (726-3475)3) Tell them card unmounting itself your GS4 (I assume also problem experienced by GS3 owners too)4) They will then confirm your information approve your return (10-15 min approval window by mine basically instantaneously) then send emails UPS return label instructions.5) BTW also asked if had magnifying glass to ID serial no. card didn't couldn't read myself (those numbers super small printed into plastic... don't me? take look yourself.) told rep couldn't read them said no problem would process without serial no. assume because send new replacement card only when receive your card send in. Makes sense.Well that's Problem (hopefully) solved. Let's see 2-3 weeks. The rep super nice about seemed all too familiar problem. KUDOS TO SANDISK FOR TAKING CARE OF IT... however would nice if there some type of communication / notice of issue besides Google info sources forums etc. spent hours maybe couple of days total hours worth thinking issue my phone / my data transfer. oh well that's how goes.I hope review helps some of out there same problem as me. GOOD LUCK!!(btw I'd give card 5 stars if problem solved patched ROM of newer cards as data transfer speeds awesome card (tested transferring data via card reader hooked to my computer)... if data transfer / remaining mounted GS4 issue never existed (pre-patch of ROM of course))UPDATE: 08/17/2013 - All went well return of SanDisk Storage card. UPS shipping took about 2 days when sent SanDisk verified warranty claim 1 day later 5 hours later same day my replacement card had been shipped. waiting new card now expect to test out soon (early next week). will update post after testing out new card. Just as reference been using 32GB Micro SD HC SanDisk card GS4 since having shipped 64GB card. Obviously it's different card not Micro SD XC kind. Other than bit slower access speeds to card zero problems.... well if don't count it's basically filled up hence why 64GB option great GS4. proves point problem early build Micro SD XC 64GB cards.I'm happy to see my review has helped some others out there. Good luck to your warranty claim. my experience SanDisk customer support has been excellent so far.Update: 08/21/2013 - Received new replacement SanDisk Storage card few days ago (shipping back to me once agreed defective short time window). Have had running Galaxy S4 for few days now without any jumps stutters card unloading middle of picture video taking. Card seems to work flawlessly as SanDisk Rep mentioned would. One would it's such short time to test after few days of use if not fixed already would have dismounted first 45 minutes... that's how often how fast occurring. so would seem problem solved. The new SD card makes phone even more responsive when moving between pictures gallery performing other tasks copying files to card. Thanks SanDisk! Unless update review by next week will know problem has been fixed.Good luck to those similar problems as we now know how to get fixed thanks to SanDisks great responsive customer service.Update: 08/31/2013 - last update to review to "close loop". The new replacement card SanDisk has been running flawlessly for about 2 weeks now. have not experienced any of initial problems. SanDisk did fix issues new batch of cards.Update: 12/09/2013 - The card has been running my GS4 flawlessly since replacing around Aug 21st. Pretty good track record so far (~ 3.5 months) so appears to fixed newly manufactured (replacement) cards.For those have left comments should change rating upwards now issue fixed (see my addition beginning of review)... When searching for solution to problem purchased product most people start 1 star reviews to see what others have experienced. especially true for products lot of reviews (this what did beginning product). Therefore think leaving 1 star adding comments beginning should clarify review.Thanks to review commenter "Da Shocker" for his input. think sums up well when comes to the value of files stored media this:"One more thing.. to those not happy the one star rating by person go ahead buy one. Take tons of pics vids save some music there then when the card crashes come back give five star. card cost $50-$100 pictures a vacation family event priceless.. "

Once cut pry your way through Sandisk's packaging will rewarded nicely-made high-performing MicroSD UHS1 flash memory. comes formatted to SD.org's standards FAT32 so it's ready to go for most applications. My single gripe about product have omitted usual small plastic box holds card adapter. use those! Since frequently switch cards between uses frequently have them storage those little boxes useful. It's way too easy to lose MicroSD.Anyway results ATTO disk benchmark:Settings (anticipating digicam use): Total length 64MB Overlapped I/O QD=4 (but never exceeds 1)Segment Size Kbytes Read/Write Kbyte/secSize Write Read.5 9904 163431 14555 170332 13454 273244 14194 353378 15065 3985316 14154 4062932 14277 4295764 13212 44291128 17567 44247256 16209 44442512 15391 444421024 17408 444422048 16229 44442[Sorry for ugly table Amazon does not support consecutive spaces including alt-255 embedded tabs]This fast for MicroSD. It's not quite up to what Sandisk achieves full size UHS1 SD cards can write over twice speed those electronically more complex cards. The Micro form factor likely doesn't permit additional hardware to achieve speeds comparable to larger cards. Note read speed lot faster than what Sandisk promises. (Note also will NOT achieve these speeds USB2 reader. You will need either USB3 built-in PCIe reader to get accurate results. do not complain to me if use USB2 reader don't achieve these speeds.)In any event you'd hard-pressed to find anything faster.My personal experience Sandisk products good. That never had anything fail me. Given very reasonable prices of these rate them as Highly Recommended.

After receiving my card inserting into my new android tablet Jelly Bean recognized did show had 59GB available. then removed card tablet inserted into my computers Win7 Vista tried to transfer files photos videos my laptop to card WOULD NOT TRANSFER! After some research internet appeared card had to reformatted new "exFAT32" to standard FAT32. All my files created Win XP Win Vista - FAT32. also have Win7 machine recently purchased can easily move all types of files between all machines memory cards flash drives could not transfer any files to card any computer as long as card formatted exFAT32. had read internet about reformatting cards working. My Win7 machine does not even have option to format to standard FAT32 only has NSTF exFAT32. My older computers have older FAT32 format option took my Vista computer Dual Core processor 1 hours to reformat card to FAT32. After reformatting able to easily transfer my files photos videos my XP Vista computers BUT not Win7 computer. The card works my tablet am able to access use all files transferred to card FAT32 my Vista computer tablet. BUT after reformatting now card only has 27GB of space available so essentially reformatted 64GB card into 32GB card. will keep card because have lot of work into reformatting transferring files hopefully future can reformat again back to exFAT32 if when exFAT32 catches OS made can seamlessly use files created both FAT32 exFAT32. seems to good card works well certain situations my advice do your research what have how will use card because not simply big GB card can used for everything every device unless ALL your files photos videos will created exFAT32 there some real draw backs to card might better off buying multiple lower GB cards if need much storage space Micro SD card. Or perhaps cards already own can reformatted into exFAT32 double capacity if your computer has exFAT32 reformat option. have not tried based my experience last few days seems would work if exFAT32 works for you. gave 3 stars because does work I feel Sandisk not fully explaining how getting 64GB out of this card the possible problems a consumer might have misleading advertising.

Hi:I ordered two card arrived next day even faster than Prime. Unfortunatey 64gb MicroSD card designed to only work ex-fat. If you're ex-fat fan don't ever plan to change card for you. been able to take all of previous 64gb MicroSD cards ordered put them adapter format them my Windows 7 desktop. NTSF fan find to much more stable tablets.With other cards aren't intentionally crippled can format card to NTSF Monday ex-fat Tuesday Fat32 Wednesday. It's ex-fat highway for SanDisk.You can use EaseUS Partition Master to format card to Fat32 for devices such as cameras mp3 players many many many others don't support ex-fat. That being said only get one shot. Once it's formatted into Fat32 attempting to format back to Exfat NTSF hoses card. couldn't reformat to NTSF no matter what tried. Once again don't bother trying to format your computer ex-fat only choice.Any card needs special utility to format to anything other than ex-fat shouldn't supported. Don't buy it! It's designed to fail.Shame Sandisk!Update 9/24/12:***************************I spoke Sandisk technical support confirmed Sandisk Ultra 64gb MicroSd cards not compatible Android 4.0 above. would for Class 10 SanDisk Ultra 64 GB microSDXC Class 10 UHS-1 Memory Card 30MB/s Adapter SDSDQUA-064G-U46A as well as SanDisk 64GB Mobile Ultra MicroSDXC Class 10 UHS-1 30MB/s Memory Card SD Adapter (NEW VERSION) - Retail Packaging Komputerbay SDXC USB Reader.I did not have any success formatting class 10 card EaseUS Partition Master. SanDisk recommended free utility HPUSBDISK.exe successfully downloaded Softpedia. unable to format card NTSF successfully converted one of cards to Fat32 for friend who wants to use SanDisk mp3 player of course not compatible ex-fat.Acting Sandisk advice am returning unopened class ten cards KomputerBay reader. spoke patient gracious tier-one tech support person party line seems consumers only use MicroSD cards phones. don't know what they're thinking: cameras mp3 players tablets adapters so on. Anyway it's known issue.I can confirm class 6 64gb MicroSD card can formatted Windows7 back forth to most any format so after returning four class 10 cards back to class six.It's still unconscionable to deliberately design these cards to incompatible. hope SanDisk will come up solution recall cards. Buyer beware.Update: 9/29/12**********************I received my two replacement class 6 64gb MicroSD cards took less than five minutes to open horrible packaging to perform quick format to NTSF. Done!I gave my friend Class 10 64gb MicroSD card formatted into Fat32 by HPUSBDISK.EXE couldn't read his computer. As turns out class 10 cards not only incompatible most devices bur also most usb card readers. Another trip across town.I can confirm IOGEAR SD/MicroSD/MMC Card Reader/Writer GFR204SD (Green/Gray) selling Amazon for $6.99 works. after countless hours of wasted effort my friend has card formatted to Fat32 works SanDisk mp3 player.Once again SanDisk has admitted these cards not compatible Androd 4.0 above being 100% of Android tablets majority of Android phones. These cards intentionally crippled by design.To quote friend:"Per SDHC standard format FAT32. SDXC (64 GB larger) spec calls for exFAT. Microsoft has limited OS to only format larger cards as exFAT will not allow FAT32. Also seems have found way to also block NTFS. Thus far few Android devices can read exFAT because refuse to pay M$ for licensing of exFAT file system. "To all masochists out there--buy card. To everyone else--unsafe any speed.

Sandisk announcement of first 128GB micro SD took internet by storm. Our phones evolved into multimedia powerhouses 5.5"-6" displays desktop grade processing power OTG support for external peripheral accessories powerful cameras more. The only missing super high capacity internal removable storage affordable price. 128GB micro SD announcement finally filled gap supported by amazon current sale of $119 shipped question still remained if some of older smartphones will able to handle/recognize capacity. personally curious considering original Note 2 spec calling for support of up to 64GB only.Now about card itself. Its their Ultra edition read speeds of up 30MB/s Class 10 performance. As part of Ultra edition it's considered to waterproof temperature-proof x-ray-proof magnet-proof also shockproof. In addition to flash card itself also includes SD adapter for compatibility digital cameras also direct reading laptops/PCs support SD card.So comes verdict: IT WORKS Note 2!!! My Note 2 all stock Verizon SCH-I605 version running stock Android 4.3. checked card first adapter my laptop then mounted my Note 2 where recognized right capacity. also ran A1 SD Benchmark app (both long accurate benchmark tests) to verify success. Read/write speed not quite near 30MB/s it's still pretty good.My opinion? card takes multimedia powerhouse Note 2 to next level!!! Now don't have to limited can store your favorite albums FLAC audio format have small library of your favorite movies stored permanently take more high def videos so on. Just always stay up to date backups. If flash card fails will covered under warranty your pictures videos will lost forever.

Once have found out can fact use such SD...go search online for HDD Raw Copy Tool HDD GURU...and will allow to make image of your old SD to apply to new SD and/or even make backup of one's SD. Since SD drives different sizes when image applied to larger...you will need to use partition manager such as MiniTool partition wizard (which free for home use) resize partition of larger drive. will allow to take advantage of whole drive space. love upgrade added space...can't go wrong price for class 10 SD of size.
